Albert Lea elementary schools will be releasing students at 11:15am through Thursday 8/27, due to the heat index threat in the afternoons. The heat index, combined with our mandatory mask requirement on school buses, creates an unsafe situation for the transportation of our students. There will be no afternoon Voluntary PreK and Early Childhood Special Education classes. Albert Lea High School and Southwest Middle School will still be released at their normal times of 1:15pm and 1:25pm.

Distance Learning Academy classes will follow their regular schedule. Secondary activities will still be held. Friday will be a Virtual day K-12, with onsite Voluntary PreK and Child Care on Friday.

post_text: Traditionally during the months of April and May, students at Southwest Middle School (6th, 7th, art and non-art) have the opportunity to design and help paint an annual mural. Since there were no physical classes during the traditional mural-painting "season" students did not have the chance to paint this year's mural. However, just before spring break and the end of this school took a complete 180, a student mural design was selected for the 2020 mural. It may not have been completed by students this time around, but, upcoming seventh grader, Bridget Dye's, mural design has become a reality and can be seen next to the 2018 and 2019 murals in the music hallway at Southwest Middle School.

post_text:
Yesterday fourth graders at Lakeview had a live guest speaker during their daily Google Meet video call. Arynn Lorentz graduated this month from Iron Range Engineering, a 4 year college in Virginia, Minnesota with a degree in mechanical engineering.

Students sent Arynn questions prior to the meeting about college and STEM careers. Some highlights:
Mechanical engineering is a broad field! People in her program have taken home and tested out future 2022 Arctic Cat snowmobile prototypes, worked on large machine projects in a John Deere factory in Iowa, and designed go carts in virtual reality.

44% of the students at Iron Range Engineering are female. So yes! girls can be engineers. Engineers help solve problems and help the world. We need all kinds of people to be engineers and share their creative thinking.

For the second year, Mark Nechanicky has had students submit writing pieces to South Central Service Cooperative writing contest.

Last Friday, 5 of his fourth grade students found out that their writing pieces were selected to be included in the 2020 writing contest anthology. Each student gets a copy of the anthology and the anthology is also sent to numerous libraries in South Central Minnesota. These students will be published authors in the Lakeview library next fall.

Typically there is an in person award ceremony at Minnesota State University in Mankato, but right now they are still discussing how to honor the authors virtually.

Here are the students and the titles of their writing pieces.

The theme for the K-12 contest was "rights and responsibilities."

Everyone should have a home

Olivia Trotman
Homework and Home

Peyton Seeger
Emily's Essay Experience

Ethan Gordon
Thieve's Hold

Nora Smith

post_text:
MINNESOTA ALL STATE CHOIR MEMBERS CHOSEN

The Minnesota Music Educators Association has chosen students for this coming years All State Music Ensembles. Three members of the Albert Lea High School Concert Choir were chosen for the All State Choirs. Nyahoth Dup will sing Alto 1 and Emma Barclay will sing Soprano 1 in the Soprano/Alto All State Choir and Caleb Banks will sing Bass II in the Tenor/Bass All State Choir. In addition, Maray Lopez was chosen as an alternate in the Alto II section. Over 1,000 students across the state auditioned in March for the ensembles and just 60 of each voice part were chosen for the choirs.

Traditionally the choirs would meet in August for a week camp to prepare their music with a renowned conductor and then meet again in February for a brush up rehearsal and performance at Orchestra Hall. This year due to COVID-19 concerns, the summer camp has been canceled. Plans are underway to meet in February 2021 with a possible extended rehearsal period to perform next winter. Congratulations choir students!

post_text: The ALHS Activities Office will begin issuing full refunds for all spring activities starting today and will continue with the process through Monday, March 30th. If you paid for a spring activity with a credit card there is no further action needed, please allow a few days for the refund to appear in your account. If by Monday, April 6th you believe have not received your refund please contact our activities office. If you paid by check or cash we will be mailing refunds to the address associated with the registration. Regardless of what MSHSL decides for the rest of the spring season, we will be issuing a full refund to families. As we are provided with more direction from the MSHSL and state agencies we will provide further information regarding the fate of our spring activities.

post_text: 10-12th Grade students in Black and White Photography spent the end of Quarter 3 designing, building, and taking photographs with pinhole cameras. These were created out of cardboard and students had to make sure the inside was completely protected from light. When it was ready to go, they made an opening with a pin and created a "shutter" to prevent light from entering until they were ready. Students then placed light sensitive paper inside and took a picture by uncovering the pinhole to let light in (exposing the image). They then brought their camera to the darkroom, removed the paper, and developed it. The negative images (pictured on top) show what was developed and the inverted photographs (on the bottom) have the colors reversed.

They then brought their camera to the darkroom, removed the paper, and developed it. In mid-March, homes across the country will begin receiving invitations to complete the 2020 Census. Once the invitation arrives, you should respond for your home in one of three ways: online, by phone, or by mail. The 2020 Census count impacts the federal funds that communities receive each year for programs and services that are critical for schools such as: Special Education, Head Start, After-School Programs, Classroom Technology, and Food Assistance.

They also recently created some landscape sketches and chose their favorite to enlarge and turn into a painting.

On Saturday, February 1st, 13 members of the 7th grade band participated in the Middle School Solo and Ensemble Contest in Owatonna, MN. Nevaeh Wacholz, Ayva Murray, and Ty Youlden won the "Outstanding Performance" award in their site, as well as earned a superior and a perfect score.
All of the students earned Superior ratings and were wonderful representatives of Albert Lea! The other students that participated were: Ruby Mykkanen, Evie Dawson, Maxx Richards, Claire Griffith, Julia Doppelhammer, Hannah Schuhmacher, Leilani Vazquez, Hailey Deming, Sophie Quam, and Kaitlin Griffith.

Take some time to celebrate those teachers who are an inspiration to students, families, and colleagues with their gift of teaching and making a difference. The purpose of the Teacher of the Year Program is to express appreciation to the many outstanding educators whose examples serve as inspiration to parents, students, and fellow teachers. In no way is the teacher to be considered the best teacher in the district, but is representative of the many teachers who daily influence the lives of students. Anyone who is currently teaching in District 241 is eligible for nomination however finalists must have completed at least three full school years in our system. Nomination forms are available via the link below or at the school offices. Forms are due by Tuesday, January 21. Thank you for your consideration!

https://www.alschools.org/TOY2020

post_text:
The 18-21 Transitions Program hosted a Holiday Open House at Brookside today. The Open House is a great opportunity for the students to practice planning and preparing for a special event.

The Albert Lea Transitions Program is for students with a disability who are between the ages of 18-21 and have completed their 12th grade year. The program offers a functional and vocational focus of skills necessary for increased independence at home, in the workplace, and the community.

post_text: Mr. Jenson's welding classes recently completed their semi-annual welding competition. This is a double elimination tournament consisting of randomly chosen welding processes and weld joints within the Wire Feed, Stick, and Oxy-Acetylene welding formats. Pictured here are 2nd period winners Caleb White (1st) and Kristian Anderson (2nd) and 4th period winners Jayden Seath (1st) and Griffin Thompson (2nd) as well as Morgan Sack, Tucker Eriksmoen, and Noah Talamantes working on their welds.

post_text: Burke Egner, STEM Teacher & Technology Integration Coach at SWMS has been awarded the Outstanding Educator Award from STEM Forward. This award recognizes K-12 professionals who strive toward the highest levels of excellence within their schools and community, with a focus on initiative and continuous improvement in every aspect of their work. Congratulations Burke!

post_text:
Southwest students in Techxploration class are learning to use block based coding to remotely pilot drones. The drones are a new addition to the curriculum and we are able to provide them through a grant received from the Albert Lea Education Foundation.

Students not only have to deal with coding to move forward, backward, left, and right, they also need to account for factors such as pitch and yaw.
